{"sequence":37,"timestamp":"2026-04-16T03:13:53.008524044Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-2-984dd490","body":"finding_summary: Propose-new-bead reconciliation is not replay-safe. `reconcile_proposed_beads_after_success` replays every accepted `ProposeNewBead` from the latest aggregate on every success-reconciliation rerun, but `handle_propose_new_bead` has no journal-based dedupe and reclassifies an already-created same-title bead as planned-elsewhere. After a post-create crash or any normal replay, the same finding can flip from `ProposedBeadCreated` into a spurious planned-elsewhere mapping instead of recognizing the prior creation.\nseverity: high\naffected_files:\n- src/contexts/automation_runtime/success_reconciliation.rs:979-1027\n- src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:2876-2901\n- src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:2957-2983\nremediation_hint: Make propose-new-bead handling idempotent by checking the milestone journal for an existing creation record keyed by run/completion_round/finding before replaying, or teach the handler to return the previously created bead instead of recording a planned-elsewhere mapping when the created bead already exists.","dedup_key":"321082c7d739ce4e59c15a55943b766cc265c50552c780fdcce41ef2fcf6ef7d","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"codex","model_id":"gpt-5.4-xhigh","reviewer_id":"reviewer-1"}],"run_id":"run-20260416021721","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
{"sequence":38,"timestamp":"2026-04-16T03:13:53.017630513Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-2-cc4143e4","body":"finding_summary: The new handler never injects any dependency edge for the bead it creates. It creates the bead, syncs, and journals it, but there is no call to `BrMutationAdapter::add_dependency` or any other graph-placement logic, so the follow-up work is left orphaned from the dependency graph even though this bead’s scope requires dependency placement and the journal is supposed to record where the bead was placed.\nseverity: medium\naffected_files:\n- src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:2921-2983\nremediation_hint: After bead creation, add the appropriate dependency edge(s) before `sync_flush()`, and include the chosen placement in the `ProposedBeadCreated` journal metadata and tests.","dedup_key":"745a20fb1a9b98e88b8e85b80837f9e868664aaaa45ae8a8f2438103f96f734f","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"codex","model_id":"gpt-5.4-xhigh","reviewer_id":"reviewer-1"}],"run_id":"run-20260416021721","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
{"sequence":39,"timestamp":"2026-04-16T03:13:53.026700433Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-2-cef2d3fb","body":"finding_summary: `resolve_created_bead_id` falls back to a raw title lookup that ignores the duplicate filters used by the defensive re-check. If `br create` stdout ever stops yielding a parseable ID, the fallback can return a closed duplicate or the active bead itself, even though those cases are explicitly rejected during pre-check, and the wrong bead ID will then be written to the journal as the created follow-up.\nseverity: medium\naffected_files:\n- src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:2756-2795\nremediation_hint: Reuse `eligible_existing_proposed_bead_match` (or a stricter predicate) in the fallback path, and prefer a structured create response or another unambiguous lookup over first-title-match resolution.","dedup_key":"24b0be437fab3b4b8b88888d77b8744a986f6d4418c3c5fddc264a5112e69866","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"codex","model_id":"gpt-5.4-xhigh","reviewer_id":"reviewer-1"}],"run_id":"run-20260416021721","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
